Dear team, thank you for delivering your presentations today.

The feedback that Eduardo an I provided is below. Please act accordingly.

I very much look forward to receiving your revised demos/files by 11:59 PM =
Thursday May 8.

Get ready for May 12 presentations to the Dean of the Sprott School of Busi=
ness. Very big day for us!

Warm regards.

Tony B

Comments on =93Up Our Game, Canada!=94 presentations the team delivered on =
May 5, 2025

  1.
Start with the why. Clearly explain the purpose of your component (e.g., co=
re product, core competence) and how it contributes to project=97before exp=
laining what you did or how. If the audience doesn't understand the purpose=
 oof your component, they won=92t engage.
  2.  Explain what your work enables for the core product and the client=92=
s products or services.
  3.  Highlight what deep research now allows you to do that was not possib=
le before.
  4.  Avoid unnecessary detail=97keep your presentation simple and focused.
  5.  Do not read directly from your slides. The audience reads faster than=
 you speak.
  6.  Avoid copying and pasting content from ChatGPT directly=97summarize y=
our insights using slides.
  7.  Practice your presentation repeatedly until delivery is smooth and co=
nfident.
  8.  Use consistent names and terminology for concepts across all presenta=
tions. Inconsistencies confuse the audience.
  9.  Consolidate all demos and files on one computer to ensure smooth tran=
sitions. Today=92s demo flow was slow and clunky.
  10. If you cannot present in person on May 12, arrange for a teammate to =
present on your behalf.
  11. Revise your files and demos and send the updated versions to Tony B v=
ia email by 11:59 PM, Thursday, May 8. He will provide prompt feedback.
  12. We do not produce videos for clients=97we co-create high-quality vide=
os with clients using advanced technology, and we continuously improve our =
methods.



